Megan McDonald
For The Pitt News

One night when Sam Reese Sheppard
was 7 years old, he learned that his pregnant
mother had been bludgeoned to death in the
bedroom next to his.

Police accused his father, Dr. Sam
Sheppard, of the crime. Sam Sheppard spent
10 years in prison before his conviction was
overturned. He was eventually acquitted.

Now, Sam Reese Sheppard is an activist
against the death penalty.

“If my father had been condemned to
death when I was 7 years old, I would have
been facing his execution at age 12,” he said.
“If that had happened, I would have checked
out a long time ago.”

Sheppard joined Daniel Hallock, a for-
mer defense—industry engineer, and several
military veterans Thursday for a discussion
in preparation for Veterans Day, “War, Peace
and Reconciliation: Working Toward a
Nonviolent Worl ” in David Lawrence Hall.

. They spoke out against the death penal-
ty and the honors of war.

The discussion followed the ﬁrst exhi-
bition at Pit of a second Veterans’ Memorial _
Wall, which veterans groups are scheduled
to unveil on the mall in Washington, D.C.,

Ion Veterans Day. Pitt’s Institute for

International Studies in Education sponsored
both events.

Sheppard said the United States’ legal
system is arrogant. It allows some cases to
spin out of control, he said, for politicians
and lawyers to use as opportunities to
advance their careers.

He said the death penalty is one exam-
ple. "

“The death penalty is a hate crime,”
Sheppard said. “My dad just wasn’t hated

enough by the jury, so they convicted him of
second-degree murder [instead of first
degree]-”.

The United States Supreme Court over-
turned the elder Sheppard’s conviction, rul-
ing that he was denied a fair trial because of
prejudicial press coverage and the judge’s
inability to control the cour1room’s “cami-
val” atmosphere. A second jury found him
not guilty, and he died shortly thereafter.

The high-proﬁle case led to the televi-
sion series and movie, “The Fugitive.”

Hallock served in the Marines before
working as an engineer in the defense indus-
try. He wrote a book, “Hell, Healing and
Resistance: Veterans Speak,” in which he
brought together 140 veterans to tell their
stories. He said the purpose of the book is to
show the ongoing suffering of many veter-
ans and their families and to help other vet-
erans cope with their experiences.

“The veterans’ search for wholeness
andhealinghasagreatdealtoteachallofus
about our own healing,” he said. “We need
to create a lot more timeand space for veter-'
ans to share their stories.”

Today, Hallock designs toys and equip-'
ment for disabled youths instead of military
helicopters. A

One World War II veteran said the mil-
itary not only dehumanizes the enemy, but
also dehumanizes its own soldiers. .

“You have a natural human instinct
against killing another person. You can’t do
it, so they desensitize you,” the veteran said.‘

He added that soldiers suffer from a
psychological and emotional wound that is
never erased.

“I came home with the guilt that I knew,
the feeling of suffering and had taken part in
it,” he said. “And it wasn’t something I could
share.”

