Ding-dong, the putz is gone!

At the end of his term in January,
House Speaker Newt Gingrich will
step down. Bowing to pressure from
both the electorate and the socalled
“revolutionary” element in the
Republican Party, Gingrich made the
decision Friday to not run for re—elec-
tion and to leave Congress altogether.

. While Gingrich’s departure is
wonderful news, Bob Livingston, R-
La., the man who challenged
Gingrich and helped orchestrate the
tide against him within the
Republican Party, is hardly the
world’s most desirable candidate for
the position. Livingston recently
campaigned to block a bill that would
have transplant organs given to
patients on the basis of need. The
way it currently stands, transplant
organs are given to patients in the
same region before patients in other
states who may need them more.

Gingrich is not the only member
of the old guard being challenged ——
forrner football player Steve Largent,
R—Okla., is challenging House

" Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-
- Texas. “What the Republican Party

needs so desperately is not reueads,

not the old has-beens, but the new .

fresh ideas [and] fresh faces,” said
Largent Friday night on CNN’s
“Larry King Live.”

Livingston and Largent, howev-
er, are the last people one could pos-
sibly associate with the term “fresh
idea.” Both are staunch conservatives
— almost every television news
report on Largent features him
addressing the house and pointing to
a chart with the Ten Commandments
-— and are willing to push forward
more controversial, right-wing ideas
than Gingrich could even contem-
plate. -An example was how
Livingston sneaked the organ-distri-_
bution rider into the Health and
Human Services section of the 1999
budget bill.

Despite Gingrich’s outspoken
nature and obvious blunders (his
$300,000 ﬁne for ethics violations,
for example), all the ills of the
Republican Party can not be put on

‘his shoulders. Though his push for

the president’s impeachment was one
of the reasons many voters were
turned off by the Republican Party,
he is not the sole reason behind the
Republicans’ relatively disappointing
election results.

It will be, for the moment, good
to get Gingrich out of the spotlight
But Gingrich’s inﬂuence will still be
felt in Washington; in his time as
House Speaker, he wielded far more
influence than Livingston can ever
hope to wield. A

