Truth and Reconciliation Commission: healing from apartheid

Michael .|. Mazza

Columnist

Under the dehumanizing system
known as apartheid, citizens of the
Republic of South Africa were classified
according to their race. Black and
mixed—race individuals were systemati-
cally deprived of basic human rights;
opponents of this system were subject to
political persecution and physical vio-
lence.

Apartheid ended in the early 1990s,

‘ but the pain of apartheid still torrnents

this nation. One group of individuals
who have tried to aid the healing process
is the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission, chaired by Archbishop
Desmond Tutu. For several years, the
commission has taken testimony from
individuals and groups who were instru-
mental in both the maintenance and dis-
mantling of apartheid. Tutu presented
the commission’s report to South African
President Nelson Mandela on Oct. 29;

. this historic event was front-page news

throughout the world.

The work of the commission has
been of particular interest to Christians
of all races in all nations. This interest
stems from the tragic fact that apartheid
was defended by the Dutch Reformed
Church of South Africa for generations.
While progressive Christian activists
like Tutu were struggling to end. this
oppressive system, their own Christian

brothers and sisters were worshipping
the false gods of racism.

Johann Kinghom has written
insightfully on the role played by
Christians in the support of apartheid in
his article “The Theology of Separate
Equality,” which has been anthologized
by editor Martin Prozesky in the 1990
collection “Christianity Amidst
Apartheid.” Kinghom notes that a tum-
ing point in the controversy over
apartheid came in 1948; in that year, the
Transvaal Synod of the Dutch Reformed
Church formally accepted a report enti-
tled “Racial and national apartheid in the
Bible.” Written by a prominent New
Testament .scholar, this report declared
that apartheid “was indeed in accordance
with the Scriptures.”

Like those American Christians who
have strip—mined the Bible for useful
texts with which to defend segregation,
disenfranchisement of women and anti-
gay legislation,. so too did South Africa’s
Dutch Reformed Church’ abuse the
Judeo-Christian Scriptures. They cited
such passages as Deuteronomy 32:8 and
Acts 17:26 in order to prove that the
racial, ethnic and geographical divisions
of mankind were God-ordained and not
to be transgressed. They pointed to the
story of the Tower of Babel (Genesis 11)
as “proof” that the desire to unify
humankind was an affront to God.

_ Despite the fall of apartheid and the
work of the commission, the hard-line

racists of the Dutch Reformed Church
refuse to give up their fears -and hatreds.
In a Dec. 17, 1997, article for Christian
Century magazine, John W. de Gruchy
noted that whereas those churches that
were the most committed to the anti-
apartheid struggle “were the first to

‘ admit their faults and failures” before the

commission, “the Dutch Reformed
Church’s confession was somewhat
bland and general.”

Indeed, many in the Dutch
Reformed Church, despite the end of
political apartheid, wish to continue
practicing racial segregation in their
Churches. As the New Pittsburgh Courier
reported on.Oct. 17, this issue remains a
topic of “heated debate” among -the
white Christians of this denomination.

While deploring the refusal of the
Dutch Reformed Church of South Africa
to decisively turn away from racism, we
should not downplay the guilt that many
American Christians bear for their
actions — or inaction — during the
struggle against apartheid. Many
American Christians willfully ignored
the cries of their black and white
brethren who pleaded for help in the
anti—apartheid struggle.

Other American Christians overtly
supported the apartheid regime, as Jim
Wallis observes in his 1997 manifesto
“Who speaks for God.” Wallis notes that
white Christian televangelist Jerry

Falwell called Tutu “a phony” in the late

